abs(x) is an implementation of getting an absolute value. |x| is the absolute value of x, and it’s x’s distance from 0 on the number line. e.g.:

<–|--|–|-->
-3 0 3
-3 is 3 digits away from 0, so |-3| = 3, and 3 is also 3 digits away from 0, so |3| = 3.[br][br][size=1]Posted on: September 21, 2008, 09:59:52 am[/size][hr]PROCESS BOOL HEART OF ANY HANDLER
